# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flow-maps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Modern cartography constitutes many theoretical and practical foundations of geographic information systems (GIS) and geographic information science (GISc).
[src:flow-maps/cartography] What is the earliest known map is a matter of some debate, both because the term "map" is not well-defined and because some artifacts that might be maps might actually be something else.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] A wall painting that might depict the ancient Anatolian city of Çatalhöyük (previously known as Catal Huyuk or Çatal Hüyük) has been dated to the late 7th millennium BCE.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Among the prehistoric alpine rock carvings of Mount Bego (France) and Valcamonica (Italy), dated to the 4th millennium BCE, geometric patterns consisting of dotted rectangles and lines are widely interpreted in archaeological literature as depicting cultivated plots.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Other known maps of the ancient world include the Minoan "House of the Admiral" wall painting from c.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] 1600 BCE, showing a seaside community in an oblique perspective, and an engraved map of the holy Babylonian city of Nippur, from the Kassite period (14th – 12th centuries BCE).
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The oldest surviving world maps are from 9th century BCE Babylonia.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] One shows Babylon on the Euphrates, surrounded by Assyria, Urartu and several cities, all, in turn, surrounded by a "bitter river" (Oceanus).
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Another depicts Babylon as being north of the center of the world.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The ancient Greeks and Romans created maps from the time of Anaximander in the 6th century BCE.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the 2nd century CE, Ptolemy wrote his treatise on cartography, Geographia.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This contained Ptolemy's world map – the world then known to Western society (*Ecumene*).
[src:flow-maps/cartography] As early as the 8th century, Arab scholars were translating the works of the Greek geographers into Arabic.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Roads were essential in the Roman world, motivating the creation of maps, called *itinerarium*, that portrayed the world as experienced via the roads.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The *Tabula Peutingeriana* is the only surviving example.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In ancient China, geographical literature dates to the 5th century BCE.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The oldest extant Chinese maps come from the State of Qin, dated back to the 4th century BCE, during the Warring States period.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the book *Xin Yi Xiang Fa Yao*, published in 1092 by the Chinese scientist Su Song, a star map on the equidistant cylindrical projection.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Although this method of charting seems to have existed in China even before this publication and scientist, the greatest significance of the star maps by Su Song is that they represent the oldest existent star maps in printed form.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Early forms of cartography of India included depictions of the pole star and surrounding constellations.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] These charts may have been used for navigation.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The Arab geographer Muhammad al-Idrisi produced his medieval atlas *Tabula Rogeriana (Book of Roger)* in 1154.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Along with the substantial text he had written, he created a world map influenced mostly by the Ptolemaic conception of the world, but with significant influence from multiple Arab geographers.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] It remained the most accurate world map for the next three centuries.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The map was divided into seven climatic zones, with detailed descriptions of each zone.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] As part of this work, a smaller, circular map depicting the south on top and Arabia in the center was made.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Al-Idrisi also made an estimate of the circumference of the world, accurate to within 10%.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the Age of Discovery, from the 15th century to the 17th century, European cartographers both copied earlier maps (some of which had been passed down for centuries) and drew their own based on explorers' observations and new surveying techniques.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The invention of the magnetic compass, telescope and sextant enabled increasing accuracy.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In 1492, Martin Behaim, a German cartographer and advisor to the king John II of Portugal, made the oldest extant globe of the Earth.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In 1507, Martin Waldseemüller produced a globular world map and a large 12-panel world wall map (*Universalis Cosmographia*) bearing the first use of the name "America." Portuguese cartographer Diogo Ribero was the author of the first known planisphere with a graduated Equator (1527).
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Italian cartographer Battista Agnese produced at least 71 manuscript atlases of sea charts.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Johannes Werner refined and promoted the Werner projection.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This was an equal-area, heart-shaped world map projection (generally called a cordiform projection) that was used in the 16th and 17th centuries.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Over time, other iterations of this map type arose; most notable are the sinusoidal projection and the Bonne projection.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The Werner projection places its standard parallel at the North Pole; a sinusoidal projection places its standard parallel at the equator; and the Bonne projection is intermediate between the two.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In 1569, mapmaker Gerardus Mercator first published a map based on his Mercator projection, which uses equally-spaced parallel vertical lines of longitude and parallel latitude lines spaced farther apart as they get farther away from the equator.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] By this construction, courses of constant bearing are conveniently represented as straight lines for navigation.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The same property limits its value as a general-purpose world map because regions are shown as increasingly larger than they actually are the further from the equator they are.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Mercator is also credited as the first to use the word "atlas" to describe a collection of maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the later years of his life, Mercator resolved to create his Atlas, a book filled with many maps of different regions of the world, as well as a chronological history of the world from the Earth's creation by God until 1568.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] He was unable to complete it to his satisfaction before he died.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Still, some additions were made to the Atlas after his death, and new editions were published after his death.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In 1570, the Brabantian cartographer Abraham Ortelius, strongly encouraged by Gillis Hooftman, created the first true modern atlas, *Theatrum Orbis Terrarum.* In a rare move, Ortelius credited mapmakers who contributed to the atlas, the list of which grew to 183 individuals by 1603.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the Renaissance, maps were used to impress viewers and establish the owner's reputation as sophisticated, educated, and worldly.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Because of this, towards the end of the Renaissance, maps were displayed with equal importance of painting, sculptures, and other pieces of art.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the sixteenth century, maps were becoming increasingly available to consumers through the introduction of printmaking, with about 10% of Venetian homes having some sort of map by the late 1500s.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In medieval times, written directions of how to get somewhere were more common than the use of maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] With the Renaissance, cartography began to be seen as a metaphor for power.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Political leaders could lay claim to territories through the use of maps, and this was greatly aided by the religious and colonial expansion of Europe.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The Holy Land and other religious places were the most commonly mapped during the Renaissance.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the late 1400s to the late 1500s, Rome, Florence, and Venice dominated map-making and trade.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] It started in Florence in the mid-to late 1400s.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Map trade quickly shifted to Rome and Venice but then was overtaken by atlas makers in the late 16th century.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Map publishing in Venice was completed with humanities and book publishing in mind, rather than just informational use.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] There were two main printmaking technologies in the Renaissance: woodcut and copper-plate intaglio, referring to the medium used to transfer the image onto paper.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In woodcut, the map image is created as a relief chiseled from medium-grain hardwood.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The areas intended to be printed are inked and pressed against the sheet.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Being raised from the rest of the block, the map lines cause indentations in the paper that can often be felt on the back of the map.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] There are advantages to using relief to make maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] For one, a printmaker doesn't need a press because the maps could be developed as rubbings.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Woodblock is durable enough to be used many times before defects appear.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Existing printing presses can be used to create the prints rather than having to create a new one.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] On the other hand, it is hard to achieve fine detail with the relief technique.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Inconsistencies in linework are more apparent in woodcut than in intaglio.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] To improve quality in the late fifteenth century, a style of relief craftsmanship developed using fine chisels to carve the wood, rather than the more commonly used knife.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In intaglio, lines are engraved into workable metals, typically copper but sometimes brass.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The engraver spreads a thin sheet of wax over the metal plate and uses ink to draw the details.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Then, the engraver traces the lines with a stylus to etch them into the plate beneath.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The engraver can also use styli to prick holes along the drawn lines, trace along them with colored chalk, and then engrave the map.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Lines going in the same direction are carved at the same time, and then the plate is turned to carve lines going in a different direction.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] To print from the finished plate, ink is spread over the metal surface and scraped off such that it remains only in the etched channels.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Then the plate is pressed forcibly against the paper so that the ink in the channels is transferred to the paper.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The pressing is so forceful that it leaves a "plate mark" around the border of the map at the edge of the plate, within which the paper is depressed compared to the margins.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Copper and other metals were expensive at the time, so the plate was often reused for new maps or melted down for other purposes.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Whether woodcut or intaglio, the printed map is hung out to dry.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Once dry, it is usually placed in another press to flatten the paper.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Any type of paper that was available at the time could be used to print the map, but thicker paper was more durable.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Both relief and intaglio were used about equally by the end of the fifteenth century.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Lettering in mapmaking is important for denoting information.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Fine lettering is difficult in woodcut, where it often turned out square and blocky, contrary to the stylized, rounded writing style popular in Italy at the time.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] To improve quality, mapmakers developed fine chisels to carve the relief.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Intaglio lettering did not suffer the troubles of a coarse medium and so was able to express the looping cursive that came to be known as cancellaresca.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] There were custom-made reverse punches that were also used in metal engraving alongside freehand lettering.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The first use of color in map-making cannot be narrowed down to one reason.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] There are arguments that color started as a way to indicate information on the map, with aesthetics coming second.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] There are also arguments that color was first used on maps for aesthetics but then evolved into conveying information.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Either way, many maps of the Renaissance left the publisher without being colored, a practice that continued all the way into the 1800s.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] However, most publishers accepted orders from their patrons to have their maps or atlases colored if they wished.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Because all coloring was done by hand, the patron could request simple, cheap color, or more expensive, elaborate color, even going so far as silver or gold gilding.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The simplest coloring was merely outlines, such as of borders and along rivers.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Wash color meant painting regions with inks or watercolors.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Limning meant adding silver and gold leaf to the map to illuminate lettering, heraldic arms, or other decorative elements.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The early modern period saw the convergence of cartographical techniques across Eurasia and the exchange of mercantile mapping techniques via the Indian Ocean.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the early seventeenth century, the Selden map was created by a Chinese cartographer.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Historians have put its date of creation around 1620, but there is debate in this regard.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This map's significance draws from historical misconceptions of East Asian cartography, the main one being that East Asians did not do cartography until Europeans arrived.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The map's depiction of trading routes, a compass rose, and scale bar points to the culmination of many map-making techniques incorporated into Chinese mercantile cartography.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In 1689, representatives of the Russian tsar and Qing Dynasty met near the border town of Nerchinsk, which was near the disputed border of the two powers, in eastern Siberia.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The two parties, with the Qing negotiation party bringing Jesuits as intermediaries, managed to work a treaty which placed the Amur River as the border between the Eurasian powers, and opened up trading relations between the two.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This treaty's significance draws from the interaction between the two sides, and the intermediaries who were drawn from a wide variety of nationalities.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Maps of the Enlightenment period practically universally used copper plate intaglio, having abandoned the fragile, coarse woodcut technology.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Use of map projections evolved, with the double hemisphere being very common and Mercator's prestigious navigational projection gradually making more appearances.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Due to the paucity of information and the immense difficulty of surveying during the period, mapmakers frequently plagiarized material without giving credit to the original cartographer.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] For example, a famous map of North America known as the "Beaver Map" was published in 1715 by Herman Moll.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This map is a close reproduction of a 1698 work by Nicolas de Fer.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] De Fer, in turn, had copied images that were first printed in books by Louis Hennepin, published in 1697, and François Du Creux, in 1664.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] By the late 18th century, mapmakers often credited the original publisher with something along the lines of, "After [the original cartographer]" in the map's title or cartouche.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In cartography, technology has continually changed in order to meet the demands of new generations of mapmakers and map users.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The first maps were produced manually, with brushes and parchment; so they varied in quality and were limited in distribution.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The advent of magnetic devices, such as the compass and much later, magnetic storage devices, allowed for the creation of far more accurate maps and the ability to store and manipulate them digitally.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Advances in mechanical devices such as the printing press, quadrant, and vernier allowed the mass production of maps and the creation of accurate reproductions from more accurate data.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Hartmann Schedel was one of the first cartographers to use the printing press to make maps more widely available.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Optical technology, such as the telescope, sextant, and other devices that use telescopes, allowed accurate land surveys and allowed mapmakers and navigators to find their latitude by measuring angles to the North Star at night or the Sun at noon.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Advances in photochemical technology, such as the lithographic and photochemical processes, make possible maps with fine details, which do not distort in shape and which resist moisture and wear.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This also eliminated the need for engraving, which further speeded up map production.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the 20th century, aerial photography, satellite imagery, and remote sensing provided efficient, precise methods for mapping physical features, such as coastlines, roads, buildings, watersheds, and topography.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The United States Geological Survey has devised multiple new map projections, notably the Space Oblique Mercator for interpreting satellite ground tracks for mapping the surface.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The use of satellites and space telescopes now allows researchers to map other planets and moons in outer space.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The ability to superimpose spatially located variables onto existing maps has created new uses for maps and new industries to explore and exploit these potentials.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] These advances brought more accuracy to geographical and location-based data and widened the range of applications for cartography, for example in the development of satnav devices.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Today most commercial-quality maps are made using software of three main types: CAD, GIS and specialized illustration software.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Spatial information can be stored in a database, from which it can be extracted on demand.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] These tools lead to increasingly dynamic, interactive maps that can be manipulated digitally.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] On the other hand, we can observe a reverse trend.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In contemporary times, there is a resurgence of interest in the most beautiful periods of cartography, with various maps being created using, for example, Renaissance-style aesthetics.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] We encounter imitators or continuators of Renaissance traditions that merge the realms of science and art.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Field-rugged computers, GPS, and laser rangefinders make it possible to create maps directly from measurements made on site.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] There are technical and cultural aspects to producing maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In this sense, maps can sometimes be said to be biased.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The study of bias, influence, and agenda in making a map is what comprise a map's deconstruction.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] A central tenet of deconstructionism is that maps have power.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Other assertions are that maps are inherently biased and that we search for metaphor and rhetoric in maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] It is claimed that the Europeans promoted an "epistemological" understanding of the map as early as the 17th century.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] An example of this understanding is that "[European reproduction of terrain on maps] reality can be expressed in mathematical terms; that systematic observation and measurement offer the only route to cartographic truth…".
[src:flow-maps/cartography] A common belief is that science heads in a direction of progress, and thus leads to more accurate representations of maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In this belief, European maps must be superior to others, which necessarily employed different map-making skills.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] "There was a 'not cartography' land where lurked an army of inaccurate, heretical, subjective, valuative, and ideologically distorted images.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Depictions of Africa are a common target of deconstructionism.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] According to deconstructionist models, cartography was used for strategic purposes associated with imperialism and as instruments and representations of power during the conquest of Africa.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The depiction of Africa and the low latitudes in general on the Mercator projection has been interpreted as imperialistic and as symbolic of subjugation due to the diminished proportions of those regions compared to higher latitudes where the European powers were concentrated.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Maps furthered imperialism and colonization of Africa in practical ways by showing basic information like roads, terrain, natural resources, settlements, and communities.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Through this, maps made European commerce in Africa possible by showing potential commercial routes and made natural resource extraction possible by depicting locations of resources.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Such maps also enabled military conquests and made them more efficient, and imperial nations further used them to put their conquests on display.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] These same maps were then used to cement territorial claims, such as at the Berlin Conference of 1884–1885.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Before 1749, maps of the African continent had African kingdoms drawn with assumed or contrived boundaries, with unknown or unexplored areas having drawings of animals, imaginary physical geographic features, and descriptive texts.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] B. d'Anville created the first map of the African continent that had blank spaces to represent the unknown territory.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In understanding basic maps, the field of cartography can be divided into two general categories: general cartography and thematic cartography.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] General cartography involves those maps that are constructed for a general audience and thus contain a variety of features.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] General maps exhibit many reference and location systems and often are produced in a series.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] For example, the 1:24,000 scale topographic maps of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) are a standard as compared to the 1:50,000 scale Canadian maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The government of the UK produces the classic 1:50,000 (replacing the older 1 inch to 1 mile) "Ordnance Survey" maps of the entire UK and with a range of correlated larger- and smaller-scale maps of great detail.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Many private mapping companies have also produced thematic map series.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Thematic cartography involves maps of specific geographic themes, oriented toward specific audiences.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] A couple of examples might be a dot map showing corn production in Indiana or a shaded area map of Ohio counties, divided into numerical choropleth classes.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] As the volume of geographic data has exploded over the last century, thematic cartography has become increasingly useful and necessary to interpret spatial, cultural and social data.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] A third type of map is known as an "orienteering," or special purpose map.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This type of map falls somewhere between thematic and general maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] They combine general map elements with thematic attributes in order to design a map with a specific audience in mind.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Oftentimes, the type of audience an orienteering map is made for is in a particular industry or occupation.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] An example of this kind of map would be a municipal utility map.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] A topographic map is primarily concerned with the topographic description of a place, including (especially in the 20th and 21st centuries) the use of contour lines showing elevation.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Terrain or relief can be shown in a variety of ways (see Cartographic relief depiction).
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In the present era, one of the most widespread and advanced methods used to form topographic maps is to use computer software to generate digital elevation models which show shaded relief.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Before such software existed, cartographers had to draw shaded relief by hand.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] One cartographer who is respected as a master of hand-drawn shaded relief is the Swiss professor Eduard Imhof whose efforts in hill shading were so influential that his method became used around the world despite it being so labor-intensive.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] A topological map is a very general type of map, the kind one might sketch on a napkin.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] It often disregards scale and detail in the interest of clarity of communicating specific route or relational information.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Beck's London Underground map is an iconic example.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Although the most widely used map of "The Tube," it preserves little of reality: it varies scale constantly and abruptly, it straightens curved tracks, and it contorts directions.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The only topography on it is the River Thames, letting the reader know whether a station is north or south of the river.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] That and the topology of station order and interchanges between train lines are all that is left of the geographic space.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Yet those are all a typical passenger wishes to know, so the map fulfills its purpose.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Modern technology, including advances in printing, the advent of geographic information systems and graphics software, and the Internet, has vastly simplified the process of map creation and increased the palette of design options available to cartographers.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This has led to a decreased focus on production skill, and an increased focus on quality design, the attempt to craft maps that are both aesthetically pleasing and practically useful for their intended purposes.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Its purpose may be as broad as teaching the major physical and political features of the entire world, or as narrow as convincing a neighbor to move a fence.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The audience may be as broad as the general public or as narrow as a single person.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Mapmakers use design principles to guide them in constructing a map that is effective for its purpose and audience.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The cartographic process spans many stages, starting from conceiving the need for a map and extending all the way through its consumption by an audience.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Conception begins with a real or imagined environment.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] As the cartographer gathers information about the subject, they consider how that information is structured and how that structure should inform the map's design.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Next, the cartographers experiment with generalization, symbolization, typography, and other map elements to find ways to portray the information so that the map reader can interpret the map as intended.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Guided by these experiments, the cartographer settles on a design and creates the map, whether in physical or electronic form.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Once finished, the map is delivered to its audience.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The map reader interprets the symbols and patterns on the map to draw conclusions and perhaps to take action.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] By the spatial perspectives they provide, maps help shape how we view the world.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Designing a map involves bringing together a number of elements and making a large number of decisions.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The elements of design fall into several broad topics, each of which has its own theory, its own research agenda, and its own best practices.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] That said, there are synergistic effects between these elements, meaning that the overall design process is not just working on each element one at a time, but an iterative feedback process of adjusting each to achieve the desired gestalt.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Some maps contain deliberate errors or distortions, either as propaganda or as a "watermark" to help the copyright owner identify infringement if the error appears in competitors' maps.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The latter often come in the form of nonexistent, misnamed, or misspelled "trap streets".
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Other names and forms for this are paper towns, fictitious entries, and copyright easter eggs.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Another motive for deliberate errors is cartographic "vandalism": a mapmaker wishing to leave their mark on the work.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Mount Richard, for example, was a fictitious peak on the Rocky Mountains' continental divide that appeared on a Boulder County, Colorado map in the early 1970s.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] It is believed to be the work of draftsman Richard Ciacci.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] The fiction was not discovered until two years later.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] In Switzerland's official maps, mapmakers have hidden illustrations of a hiker, fish, marmot, and more for over a century.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] Sandy Island in New Caledonia is an example of a fictitious location that stubbornly survives, reappearing on new maps copied from older maps while being deleted from other new editions.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] With the emergence of the internet and Web mapping, technologies allow for the creation and distribution of maps by people without proper cartographic training are readily available.
[src:flow-maps/cartography] This has led to maps that ignore cartographic conventions and are potentially misleading.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] In mathematics, and more specifically in graph theory, a **directed graph** (or **digraph**) is a graph that is made up of a set of vertices connected by directed edges, often called **arcs**.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] It differs from an ordinary or undirected graph, in that the latter is defined in terms of unordered pairs of vertices, which are usually called *edges*, *links* or *lines*.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The aforementioned definition does not allow a directed graph to have multiple arrows with the same source and target nodes, but some authors consider a broader definition that allows directed graphs to have such multiple arcs (namely, they allow the arc set to be a multiset).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] Sometimes these entities are called **directed multigraphs** (or **multidigraphs**).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] On the other hand, the aforementioned definition allows a directed graph to have loops (that is, arcs that directly connect nodes with themselves), but some authors consider a narrower definition that does not allow directed graphs to have loops.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] Directed graphs without loops may be called **simple directed graphs**, while directed graphs with loops may be called *loop-digraphs* (see section Types of directed graph).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] An arc (*x*, *y*) is considered to be directed *from* *x* *to* *y*; *y* is called the *head* and *x* is called the *tail* of the arc; *y* is said to be a *direct successor* of *x* and *x* is said to be a *direct predecessor* of *y*.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] If a path leads from *x* to *y*, then *y* is said to be a *successor* of *x* and *reachable* from *x*, and *x* is said to be a *predecessor* of *y*.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The arc (*y*, *x*) is called the *reversed arc* of (*x*, *y*).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a multidigraph with loops is the integer-valued matrix with rows and columns corresponding to the vertices, where a nondiagonal entry *a**ij* is the number of arcs from vertex *i* to vertex *j*, and the diagonal entry *a**ii* is the number of loops at vertex *i*.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph is a logical matrix, and is unique up to permutation of rows and columns.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] Another matrix representation for a directed graph is its incidence matrix.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] For a vertex, the number of head ends adjacent to a vertex is called the *indegree* of the vertex and the number of tail ends adjacent to a vertex is its *outdegree* (called *branching factor* in trees).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The indegree of *v* is denoted deg−(*v*) and its outdegree is denoted deg+(*v*).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] A vertex with deg−(*v*) = 0 is called a *source*, as it is the origin of each of its outgoing arcs.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] Similarly, a vertex with deg+(*v*) = 0 is called a *sink*, since it is the end of each of its incoming arcs.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] If for every vertex *v* ∈ *V*, deg+(*v*) = deg−(*v*), the graph is called a *balanced directed graph*.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The degree sequence of a directed graph is the list of its indegree and outdegree pairs; for the above example we have degree sequence ((2, 0), (2, 2), (0, 2), (1, 1)).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The degree sequence is a directed graph invariant so isomorphic directed graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a directed graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic digraphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The directed graph realization problem is the problem of finding a directed graph with the degree sequence a given sequence of positive integer pairs.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] This problem can either be solved by the Kleitman–Wang algorithm or by the Fulkerson–Chen–Anstee theorem.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] A directed graph is *weakly connected* (or just *connected*) if the undirected *underlying graph* obtained by replacing all directed edges of the graph with undirected edges is a connected graph.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] A directed graph is *strongly connected* or *strong* if it contains a directed path from *x* to *y* (and from *y* to *x*) for every pair of vertices (*x*, *y*).
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] The *strong components* are the maximal strongly connected subgraphs.
[src:flow-maps/directed-graph] A connected rooted graph (or *flow graph*) is one where there exists a directed path to every vertex from a distinguished *root vertex*.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] Flow diagrams are used to structure and order a complex system, or to reveal the underlying structure of the elements and their interaction.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] The term flow diagram is used in theory and practice in different meanings.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] Most commonly the flow chart and flow diagram are used in an interchangeable way in the meaning of a representation of a process.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] ... is a diagram that visually displays interrelated information such as events, steps in a process, functions, etc., in an organized fashion, such as sequentially or chronologically.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] [is] a graphic representation of the physical route or flow of people, materials, paperworks, vehicles, or communication associated with a process, procedure plan, or investigation.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] In the second definition the meaning is limited to the representation of the physical route or flow.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] An example of such a diagram is the illustration of the flows in a nuclear submarine propulsion system, which shows different streams back and forth in the system.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] The representation of such a system can be supplemented by one or more flowcharts, which show the sequence of one of the flows in one direction, or any of the control flows to manage the system.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] The physical movement of objects from one location to another can also be visualized in a mix of maps and flowchart or sankey diagram, which are called flow maps.
[src:flow-maps/flow-diagram] Flow maps can indicate on a map, what flows, moves or migrates, in which direction, and in which quantities etc.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] A **flow map** is a type of thematic map that uses linear symbols to represent movement between locations.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] It may thus be considered a hybrid of a map and a flow diagram.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The movement being mapped may be that of anything, including people, highway traffic, trade goods, water, ideas, telecommunications data, etc.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The wide variety of moving material, and the variety of geographic networks through they move, has led to many different design strategies.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Some cartographers have expanded this term to any thematic map of a linear network, while others restrict its use to maps that specifically show movement of some kind.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Many flow maps use line width proportional to the amount of flow, making them similar to other maps that use proportional size, including cartograms (altering region area), and proportional point symbols.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The earliest known map to visually represent the volume of flow were two maps by engineer Henry Drury Harness, published in 1838 as part of a report on the potential for railroad construction in Ireland, showing the quantity of cargo traffic by road and canal.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] In subsequent years, others experimented with the technique in Europe, until it was mastered by Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] During the 1850s and 1860s, Minard published forty-two flow maps on a wide variety of topics among his *cartes figuratives*.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Among these is his 1869 map of the French invasion of Russia in 1812-1813, which has been called "the best statistical graphic ever drawn." Many of Minard's maps use design techniques that have yet to be improved upon, even in the age of computer graphics.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] During the 1980s, Waldo Tobler conducted experiments to create flow maps by computer.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Early computer-generated maps were not up to Minard standards, but Geographic information system (GIS) and graphics software has improved in the ability to design flow maps.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] A wide variety of flow maps have been created since the 1830s, showing movement in many forms.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] These are not distinct types of maps; a flow map may portray any of all of these aspects simultaneously.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The types of phenomena that have been the subject of flow maps are varied.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Topics relating to human geography include: migration, travel, international trade, logistics, public utilities (water, sewer, electricity, telecommunications), and traffic, among others.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Others relate to physical geography: streamflow, wind, wildlife migration, etc.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The variance of flow maps in subject matter, and the relative importance of Imhof's aspects of flow, has led to a number of design strategies.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] In a 1987 thesis, Mary Parks identified several distinct types of flow maps, which has been widely cited although her list was not comprehensive and more are included here.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] These types are prototypical; actual maps can combine some aspects of several types.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] In this type, the primary intent is to show the existence of a connection between two places, often accompanied by a representation of the volume of flow and/or direction.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The route is generally not important to the audience, so connecting lines are often straight or slightly curved.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] A common example of this form is the airline route map.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Parks distinguished *radial* maps (emanating from a single origin or destination) from *network* maps (interconnecting a number of nodes), but this is a difference in the geographic pattern; the design is very similar for both types.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Origin-destination maps have a unique design focus on the schematic shape of the connecting lines.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Straight lines are easy to draw, but can cause issues, especially when longer lines and shorter lines are collinear, obscuring each other and their destinations.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] For these reasons, curved lines, typically circular arcs, are preferred as more aesthetically pleasing.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] They also have the ability to be adjusted to avoid intervening lines and points.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Early automated line generation algorithms were typically straight lines, but recent algorithms have been successful at creating curved lines.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] This type is exemplified by a balanced focus on origin-destination nodes, the routes of travel between them (usually highly generalized), and the volume of flow.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The most common example, dating back to Minard, is a map showing shipping between a set of node regions or port cities, along common sea lanes.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] In a distribution map, paths leave the origin with a width proportional to the total of several destinations, then divide as routes "distribute" toward each destination.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Designing distribution maps requires some care and craft in drafting the flow lines so they divide with proper widths, and at smooth curving angles.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Computation experiments have shown the potential for generating these automatically, but today most are drawn semi-manually using GIS and graphics software.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] This type of flow map originally dates back to the Harness map of Ireland.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] It focuses more on the routes of the network than its origin/destination nodes.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The routes may be precise or highly generalized (as in many transit maps), and may or may not represent amount or speed of flow.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] A common example is a map of highway traffic.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Not all flow occurs along linear networks; two- and three-dimensional masses can also flow, especially water (e.g., ocean current) and air (wind).
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Their movement can be modeled as a vector field, in which the magnitude and direction of movement could be measured at any point in space.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] In Imhof's list above, a map that visualizes this, often called a *mass flow map* or *continuous flow map*, focuses on direction and speed of flow, while other aspects such as origin/destination and route of travel are largely meaningless.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] In 1688, Edmund Halley mapped the trade winds using an array of short line segments oriented in the direction of air flow.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] In early 20th Century weather maps, this technique was elaborated into *wind barbs*, complex symbols used to indicate wind speed as well as direction.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] *Unit vectors* and *streamlets* have been proposed as a general term for point-based flow symbols, but neither is in wide usage.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] These can be readily generated by computer algorithms, especially using raster GIS data or sample point data (e.g., weather stations).
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] This approach is more akin to proportional point symbols than a typical flow map.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Another visualization option for vector fields is to draw *streamlines*, which connect points that would flow into each other; this has been commonly used to represent ocean currents since the early 19th Century.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] Among Tobler's 1981 computer algorithms were models of vector fields to generate "streaklines," and subsequent work has improved results.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The most common technique to visualize the amount or speed of flow is through the visual variable of size, specifically line weight (usually measured in points or millimeters).
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] That said, size is much more intuitive for total amount, so other visual variables (such as color hue or color value) may also be considered for speed.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] The following methods for determining line weights is very similar to the scaling methods for proportional symbol maps.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] This helps readers make intuitive judgements about relative value ratios based on relative weights; a line that is twice as thick as another represents twice the value.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] However, when there is a very high level of variation between the highest and lowest values (generally, more than 25:1, although this depends on the geography of the flow network and the design), the resultant map can be problematic, with overwhelming thick lines and almost invisible thin lines.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] A third alternative is to simply use ordinal weights (thick, medium, thin, etc.) to represent an ordinal variable or a quantitative variable that has been classified (often called *range grading* in this context).
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] This also loses the ability of readers to intuitively judge value differences, but has the advantage of overall simplicity.
[src:flow-maps/flow-map] For all of these types of scaling, the legend typically shows a sample set of line weights with their respective values, in a fashion similar to the legend of a proportional symbol map.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams can also visualize the energy accounts, material flow accounts on a regional or national level, and cost breakdowns.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] The diagrams are often used in the visualisation of material flow analysis.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams emphasize the major transfers or flows within a system.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] They help locate the most important contributions to a flow.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] They often show conserved quantities within defined system boundaries.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams are named after Irish Captain Matthew Henry Phineas Riall Sankey, who used this type of diagram in 1898 in a classic figure (see diagram) showing the energy efficiency of a steam engine.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] The original charts in black and white displayed just one type of flow (e.g., steam); using colors for different types of flows lets the diagram express additional variables.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Over time, it became a standard model used in science and engineering to represent heat balance, energy flows, material flows, and since the 1990s this visual model has been used in life-cycle assessment of products.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] One of the most famous Sankey diagrams is Charles Minard's Map of Napoleon's Russian Campaign of 1812.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] It is a flow map, overlaying a Sankey diagram onto a geographical map.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] It was created in 1869, predating Sankey's diagram of 1898.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Minard had used this form of diagram for visualising flow of goods and transport of people from at least since 1844.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams are often used in fields of science, especially physics.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] They are used to represent energy inputs, useful output, and wasted output.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] The US Energy Information Administration (EIA) produces numerous Sankey diagrams annually in its *Annual Energy Review* which illustrate the production and consumption of various forms of energy.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] The US Department of Energy's Lawrence Livermore Laboratory maintains a site of Sankey diagrams, including US energy flow and carbon flow.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Eurostat, the Statistical Office of the European Union, has developed an interactive Sankey web tool to visualise energy data by means of flow diagrams.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] The tool allows the building and customisation of diagrams by playing with different options (country, year, fuel, level of detail).
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] The International Energy Agency (IEA) created an interactive Sankey web application that details the flow of energy for the entire planet.
[src:flow-maps/sankey-diagram] Users can select specific countries, points of time back to 1990, and modify the arrangement of various flows within the Sankey diagram.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] A **thematic map** is a type of map that portrays the geographic pattern of a particular subject matter (theme) in a geographic area.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] This usually involves the use of map symbols to visualize selected properties of geographic features that are not naturally visible, such as temperature, language, or population.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] In this, they contrast with general reference maps, which focus on the location (more than the properties) of a diverse set of physical features, such as rivers, roads, and buildings.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Alternative names have been suggested for this class, such as *special-subject* or *special-purpose maps*, *statistical maps*, or *distribution maps*, but these have generally fallen out of common usage.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Thematic mapping is closely allied with the field of Geovisualization.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Several types of thematic maps have been invented, starting in the 18th and 19th centuries, as large amounts of statistical data began to be collected and published, such as national censuses.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] These types, such as choropleth maps, isarithmic maps, and chorochromatic maps, use very different strategies for representing the location and attributes of geographic phenomena, such that each is preferable for different forms of phenomena and different forms of available data.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] According to Arthur Robinson, thematic maps were largely an Industrial Age innovation, with some Enlightenment-era roots; almost all of the modern graphical techniques were invented between 1700 and 1850.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Prior to this, the most important cartographic development was the production of accurate general base maps.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Their accuracy improved slowly, and even in the mid-17th century, they were usually of poor quality; but they were good enough to display basic information, allowing the production of the first thematic maps.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] One of the earliest thematic maps was one entitled *Designatio orbis christiani* (1607) by Jodocus Hondius, showing the dispersion of major religions using map symbols, in the French edition of his *Atlas Minor* (1607).
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] An early contributor to thematic mapping in England was the English astronomer Edmond Halley (1656–1742), who introduced the Enlightenment conception of the thematic map as a tool for scientific thinking.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] His first significant cartographic contribution was a star chart of the constellations of the Southern Hemisphere, made during his stay on St.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] In that same year he also published his first terrestrial map in an article about trade winds, and this map is called the first meteorological chart.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] In 1701 he published the "New and Correct Chart Shewing the Variations of the Compass", see first image, the first chart to show lines of equal magnetic variation and possibly the first isarithmic map.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Early chorochromatic (nominal area-class) maps also appeared in the late 18th century as scientific instruments for exploring geographic phenomena such as geology and language.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The early to middle 19th century could be considered, as Robinson called it, a "golden age" of thematic mapping, when many of the current techniques were invented or further developed.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] For example, the earliest known choropleth map was created in 1826 by Charles Dupin.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Based on this work Louis-Léger Vauthier (1815–1901) developed the population contour map, a map that shows the population density of Paris in 1874 by isolines.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] One of the most influential early works of thematic cartography was a small booklet of five maps produced in 1837 by Henry Drury Harness as part of a government report on the potential for construction of railroads in Ireland.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Included were early chorochromatic and flow maps, and possibly the first proportional point symbol and dasymetric maps.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Another example of early thematic mapping comes from London physician John Snow.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Though disease had been mapped thematically, Snow's cholera map in 1854 is the best-known example of using thematic maps for analysis.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Essentially, his technique and methodology anticipated the principles of a geographic information system (GIS).
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Starting with an accurate base map of a London neighborhood which included streets and water pump locations, Snow mapped out the incidence of cholera deaths.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The emerging pattern centered around one particular pump in Broad Street.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] At Snow's request, the handle of the pump was removed, and new cholera cases ceased almost at once.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Further investigation of the area revealed that the Broad Street pump was near a cesspit under the home of the outbreak's first cholera victim.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Charles Joseph Minard has been hailed as perhaps the first master of thematic mapping and information visualization.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] In the 1850s and 1860s, he integrated thematic maps (especially flow maps) with statistical charts to create visual narratives, most notably his 1869 map of Napoleon's 1812 invasion of Europe.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] By the early 20th century, established methods were in place for manually drafting a variety of thematic maps, but they were still produced in far fewer numbers than general reference maps, and occupied a relatively small portion of cartographic education.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The most common purpose of a thematic map is to portray the geographic distribution of one or more phenomena.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Sometimes this distribution is already familiar to the cartographer, who wants to communicate it to an audience, while at other times the map is created to discover previously unknown patterns (as a form of Geovisualization).
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Thematic maps accomplish these two goals by leveraging the natural ability of the human visual perception system to recognize patterns in a complex visual field, which is necessary for common tasks such as object recognition.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] By focusing on a single subject matter, the thematic map is typically intended to be used for a narrower range of tasks than a reference map.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Provide general information about spatial patterns.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Cartographers use many methods to create thematic maps.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] For example, a cartogram technique could be used to distort the sizes of countries proportional to one variable, with the countries being filled with colors representing a second variable using the choropleth technique.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] A choropleth map shows statistical data aggregated over predefined regions, such as countries or states, by coloring or shading these regions.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] For example, countries with higher rates of infant mortality might appear darker on a choropleth map.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The summary variable being mapped may be nominal or 67quantitative, but usually represents a geographic field.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Visual variables filling each region are used to represent each aggregate summary value: hue is commonly used for qualitative variables, such as predominant land use, while lightness is most common for quantitative differences, such as population density.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Choropleth maps are the most popular form of thematic map due to their intuitive nature, widespread availability of such aggregate statistical data, and GIS data for common regions.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The loss of information inherent in aggregate information can result in interpretation issues such as the Ecological fallacy and the Modifiable areal unit problem.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Choropleth maps, in almost all cases, must employ normalized or rate data (such as people per square mile, or disease cases per 100,000) to avoid creating a misleading map.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] This step is often ignored, leading to potentially misleading maps.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The proportional symbol technique uses point symbols of different sizes (height, length, area, or volume) to represent quantitative statistical values associated with different areas or locations within the map.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] For example, a disc may be shown at the location of each city in a map, with the area of the disc being proportional to the population of the city.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] This type of map is useful for visualization when raw data cannot be dealt with as a ratio or proportion.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Although circles are the most typical symbol because they are more compact due to their low perimeter to area ratio, studies show that it is easier for the reader to estimate the size of the symbol if it is a square or a bar.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Proportional symbol maps are commonly used for variables representing total counts or amounts.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] A cartogram is a map that intentionally distorts geographic space based on a given variable, usually by scaling features so their size is proportional to their value of the variable.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] For example, the countries of the world could be scaled proportional to their population.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The features being distorted may be lines (such as making the length of subway lines proportional to travel time), but most commonly it is regions that are scaled.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The distorted shapes are sometimes used as a basis for additional thematic mapping techniques, such as the choropleth, and can be used to display absolute data not appropriate for choropleth maps.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Isarithmic maps, also known as contour maps or isoline maps, depict continuous quantitative fields (sometimes conceptualized as "statistical surfaces" by cartographers), such as precipitation or elevation by partitioning space into regions, each containing a consistent range of values of the field.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The boundary of each region, an *isoline*, thus represents the set of locations of constant value.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] For example, on a topographic map, each contour line indicates an area at the listed elevation.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] A chorochromatic or area-class map represents a categorical or nominal variable distributed over space (also known as a discrete field), by using different area symbols (usually color hue) to represent regions of homogeneous value.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Common examples include maps of surface geology, soil, vegetation, land use, city zoning, and climate type.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] A dot distribution map places small point symbols over a given space to indicate the distribution of a given phenomenon.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The location of each dot may represent the actual location of a single instance, as in the map made by Dr.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Snow during the 1854 Broad Street cholera outbreak, where each dot represented one death due to cholera.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Alternatively, aggregate statistical data (the same used in choropleth maps) may be mapped by randomly placing dots within each aggregation region (e.g., country, state, county) to show the general density of instances; this latter form is usually called a *dot density map*.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Flow maps are maps that use line symbols to portray movement or relationship between two or more places, such as air travel, monetary aid, or economic trade.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The lines may be schematic straight lines or curves, or may represent the actual travel route.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Some flow maps simply show the presence of connections, while others use visual variables such as size (width) or color to represent the properties of each connection.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] A dasymetric map is an alternative to a choropleth map.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] As with a choropleth map, data are collected by enumeration units.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] But instead of mapping the data so that the region appears uniform, *ancillary information* is used to estimate a more detailed distribution of the phenomenon within each enumeration unit.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] For example, land cover data (forest, water, grassland, urbanization) may be used to refine the distribution of county-level population density.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] While the thematic information is the core of a thematic map, other geographic features may also be included as *reference information*.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] The primary purpose of reference information is to establish the location of the thematic information in a context understood by the map readers (i.e., to answer questions such as "where is this red region in the real world?").
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] Common reference layers include government administrative boundaries, roads, cities, a latitude/longitude graticule, or even terrain.
[src:flow-maps/thematic-map] These layers play a secondary role in the use of the map, so they are usually included sparingly, and symbolized to be low in the visual hierarchy, but not so faded that they cannot be used.
